I had to read a lot of the inspirations in order to understand what the idea was in the first place. It was describing a technology, but what about it? Besides having trouble understanding the technology, I had no context about what the generated ideas were supposed to be like. I feel this is going to be difficult to explain, but when I read the technology I felt "What about it? What is it that you are asking me about something that's a description of something?" So it took a while of reading inspirations to get what it is that you wanted. Now some five minutes had gone by after I read and re-read the technology a number of times, wondered about it, wondered what you were looking for, and read quite a few inspirations. The ticking clock made me crazy, extremely anxious, and not at all playful. I thought how normally if I sat down to do something like this I might spend half an hour thinking about the technology before I even started the ideas, and I would spend at least an hour brainstorming ideas. Then I would come back to it, probably on another day, read things over and do it again, while thinking about it generally at off moments. I am really not the right person to be confused about what something is and then have good ideas in the rest of the ten minutes. I realize that part of it is the ticking clock, which as I said made me anxious and non-playful. This is not advice or recommendations, just a report of my experience with the HIT and how I would normally brainstorm at extreme leisure.
